cmCourseInfo.description: Structure of the human body and its relationship to function. Basic Human Histology, Gross Anatomy, and Neuroanatomy. Some content is delivered using online modules.
cmCourseInfo.title: Human Anatomy and Histology

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

ANA300Y1 meets four hours per week for lectures. 

One-hour tutorials are offered six time per week. Students must enrol in a tutorial to attend synchronously.

Delivery Instructions

Course content will be taught using a mixture of e-modules and either synchronous or asynchronous lectures. Synchronous lectures will be recorded for asynchronous attendance. When content is delivered asynchronously, either via an e-module or recorded lecture, students will be given the opportunity to ask questions of the Course Director during a corresponding synchronous session during the scheduled class time. Weekly synchronous tutorials will emphasize practical anatomy and will not be recorded; students must attend their online tutorial at their scheduled time. Students must have access to a stable internet connection.

cmCourseInfo.description: Human embryology from fertilization to the end of the fetal period. Current concepts in mammalian morphogenesis applied to the development of the various organ systems; etiologies and pathogenesis of some of the more common human congenital abnormalities.
cmCourseInfo.title: Human Embryology

cmCourseInfo.description: A focussed series of Anatomical dissections will be made and the surgical implications of the findings will be the subject of seminars. Attitudes to dissection of the human body, complications of surgery and other relevant issues will be discussed.
cmCourseInfo.title: Anatomy Dissection
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: ANA300Y1 and permission of department. Normally a "B+" standing will be required

cmCourseInfo.description: This course will cover musculoskeletal anatomy (both upper and lower limb) topics with an emphasis on applying detailed anatomical review, biomechanical principles and research evidence to explain or clarify exercise principles and myths.
cmCourseInfo.title: Anatomy  in Application:  Exercise & Biomechanics

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides an opportunity for students to participate in an individual research project in a particular topic of study including, but not limited to histology, cellular and molecular biology, developmental biology, neuroscience and gross anatomy. Students are mentored and supervised by research scientists and faculty associated with the University of Toronto. These research project may include areas such as Histology, Cellular or Molecular Biology, Developmental Biology, Neuroanatomy or Gross Anatomy. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
cmCourseInfo.title: Independent Research Project
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: Permission from proposed supervisor and approval from the course coordinator.

notes.name: Course Note
notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

Students must submit a completed ANA496H1F ballot to anatomy@utoronto.ca by Friday, September 4th, before being approved and enrolled. Ballots are available on the course website: https://surgery.utoronto.ca/division-anatomy-arts-science-undergraduate-courses

Delivery Instructions

Course workload is self-paced, ensuring deadlines are met. Weekly meetings may be scheduled, this is up to each Supervisor's discretion and needs for each individual's project. Students need access to a stable internet connection, and Quercus. Students may need access to software required for their particular research project. Three seminars will be offered throughout the term during the Tutorial Time and attendance will be mandatory for one of the seminars.
